Getting Started in R: Objects, Functions and Indexing

Even if we know nothing about the R language, we can still perform basic operations by using it like a calculator. If we type 2 + 3 into the console and press enter, we get this result:

[1] 5

The plus sign we used in this case is called an operator. Operators are simply symbols that represent some sort of action. All the standard operators you would use on a calculator can also be used in R. However, if we want to use R to do something more complex, we need to understand objects.

What is an object in R?

R is an object-oriented programming language. One way to understand how objects work in programming is to look at how objects work in real life.

We tend to group objects by their structure. For example, there are many objects we call cars, and they all tend to share similarities in structure - they have wheels, windows, doors, etc. An individual car such as my car or your car is an instance of this structure. Cars also have a set of properties such as make, model, year and color. Each individual car has some variation of these properties.

Objects in R work in a similar way.

In the diagram above, we are looking at three data structures often used in R: vectors, matrices and data frames. We can create individual objects from these data structures, and those objects have their own properties.

Other types of data structures exist, but for now well focus on these three. To begin, lets take a look at vectors.

Vectors

A vector is a simple sequence of elements. One way to create a vector object is to use the c() or concatenate function. Lets create a vector of numbers.

Notice the # symbols below. These indicate notes, or comments, that can be used to document whats going on in our code without interfering with the code itself. Everything to the right of the # is ignored by R.

myVector <- c(1, 2, 3, 4) #assignment of object
myVector #evaluation of object
[1] 1 2 3 4

The <- operator looks like a left-pointing arrow. Its used for assignment - in this case, to assign our sequence of numbers to an object called myVector. We can then evaluate, or look at our object, by simply typing its name.

An important thing to know about vectors is that all the elements within one use the same data type. In the example above, we created a numeric vector. We can also create a character vector using text. Note the quotation marks:

stuff <- c("car", "apple", "book")
stuff
[1] "car"   "apple" "book"

Another type of data is logical data. Below, we create a logical vector. Note the ALL CAPS.

answers <- c(TRUE, FALSE, FALSE, TRUE)
answers
[1]  TRUE FALSE FALSE  TRUE

Matrices

A matrix is an object with data elements in two dimensions, meaning it has both rows and columns. Below, well create a matrix of numbers 1 through 12. Well give it 3 rows and 4 columns.

myMatrix <- matrix(data=1:12, nrow=3, ncol=4)
myMatrix
     [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4]
[1,]    1    4    7   10
[2,]    2    5    8   11
[3,]    3    6    9   12

Notice that the matrix has row names (like [1,]) and column names (like [,1]). Well get into those later.

Like vectors, matrices only include data of the same type. If we want to use a two dimensional object with multiple data types, we need a data frame.

Data Frames

Data frames have a similar structure to matrices, but they allow us to mix data types. Most data that we bring into R from an outside source (such as a spreadsheet) will be stored in a data frame.

R comes with a collection of built-in data frames that we can use for practice or testing our code. Lets look at one called CO2 which contains data from a study on plants and carbon dioxide. Its a long data set, so well just look at the first few rows using the head() function.

head(x=CO2)
  Plant   Type  Treatment conc uptake
1   Qn1 Quebec nonchilled   95   16.0
2   Qn1 Quebec nonchilled  175   30.4
3   Qn1 Quebec nonchilled  250   34.8
4   Qn1 Quebec nonchilled  350   37.2
5   Qn1 Quebec nonchilled  500   35.3
6   Qn1 Quebec nonchilled  675   39.2

Like the matrix we looked at earlier, data frames have row and column names. In this case, the column names are the actual variables used in the study (plant, treatment, etc.) and the row names are numbered.

Functions

Just as we can handle and manipulate objects in the real world, we can do so with objects in R by using functions. So far, weve already used three functions: c(), matrix() and head(). Functions take some sort of input and then produce some sort of output. Input is given through arguments within the parentheses next to the function name.

For example, the head() function uses an argument called x which takes the input of an object. It also uses an argument called n which allows us to specify how many rows we want to look at. The default number is 6, so if we dont provide the n argument, it will automatically show us the top 6 rows. However, if we want to look at the top 3 rows, we can do this

head(x=CO2, n=3)
  Plant   Type  Treatment conc uptake
1   Qn1 Quebec nonchilled   95   16.0
2   Qn1 Quebec nonchilled  175   30.4
3   Qn1 Quebec nonchilled  250   34.8

If we already know the order that our arguments are supposed to be in for our particular function, we dont actually need to type in the names of the arguments. We can simply provide the values that we want to input and get the same results.

head(CO2, 3)
  Plant   Type  Treatment conc uptake
1   Qn1 Quebec nonchilled   95   16.0
2   Qn1 Quebec nonchilled  175   30.4
3   Qn1 Quebec nonchilled  250   34.8

R comes with lots of functions to use on our objects, including those you might find on a calculator, such as log(). log() takes an object as input, and outputs the natural log.

a <- c(3, 8, 12) #create a vector called "a" with 3 numbers
log(a) #output the natural log of all 3 numbers
[1] 1.098612 2.079442 2.484907

If we want to know more about the log() function, we can ask R to show us documentation for it with a question mark.

?log

We can also search R documentation for anything containing the word log with double question marks.

??log

Keep in mind, we arent just limited to the functions built into base R. Its common practice to use third-party functions by installing packages. We can also create our own functions. Those options will be covered in greater detail after weve gained more experience in R.

Indexing

Our objects in R often contain multiple elements, but sometimes we want to focus on just a single element. For example, consider the stuff vector we created earlier.

stuff
[1] "car"   "apple" "book"

What if we only want to look at the second element of our vector? How can we tell R to focus on that second element? We do so using indexing. Each element of an object is given a numerical index based on its position, starting with 1. So, in this case, car has an index of 1, apple an index of 2, and book an index of 3. Indices are surrounded by square brackets. To view only the second element in our vector, we do this

stuff[2]
[1] "apple"

That works well enough for vectors, but what about two dimensional objects like matrices and data frames? Remember our numeric matrix?

myMatrix
     [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4]
[1,]    1    4    7   10
[2,]    2    5    8   11
[3,]    3    6    9   12

Look at the row and column names again. Theyre surrounded by square brackets! Every element in the matrix has TWO indices, one for the row and one for the column. Lets look at the element in the third row and second column.

myMatrix[3,2]
[1] 6

We can also focus on an entire row or entire column of our matrix by using only one index. We still need to include the comma in the correct position, though. For example, to view only the second row:

myMatrix[2,]
[1]  2  5  8 11

Or the fourth column:

myMatrix[,4]
[1] 10 11 12

What if we want to multiply all the numbers in that fourth column by 2, and store the results in a separate vector object?

newVector <- myMatrix[,4] * 2
newVector
[1] 20 22 24

If our object has words for column names (something that often happens when we load a data frame), we can also use those to reference a column by way of a dollar sign. For example, to view the uptake column of our CO2 data frame, we can do either this:

CO2$uptake
 [1] 16.0 30.4 34.8 37.2 35.3 39.2 39.7 13.6 27.3 37.1 41.8 40.6 41.4 44.3
[15] 16.2 32.4 40.3 42.1 42.9 43.9 45.5 14.2 24.1 30.3 34.6 32.5 35.4 38.7
[29]  9.3 27.3 35.0 38.8 38.6 37.5 42.4 15.1 21.0 38.1 34.0 38.9 39.6 41.4
[43] 10.6 19.2 26.2 30.0 30.9 32.4 35.5 12.0 22.0 30.6 31.8 32.4 31.1 31.5
[57] 11.3 19.4 25.8 27.9 28.5 28.1 27.8 10.5 14.9 18.1 18.9 19.5 22.2 21.9
[71]  7.7 11.4 12.3 13.0 12.5 13.7 14.4 10.6 18.0 17.9 17.9 17.9 18.9 19.9

Or this:

CO2[,5]
 [1] 16.0 30.4 34.8 37.2 35.3 39.2 39.7 13.6 27.3 37.1 41.8 40.6 41.4 44.3
[15] 16.2 32.4 40.3 42.1 42.9 43.9 45.5 14.2 24.1 30.3 34.6 32.5 35.4 38.7
[29]  9.3 27.3 35.0 38.8 38.6 37.5 42.4 15.1 21.0 38.1 34.0 38.9 39.6 41.4
[43] 10.6 19.2 26.2 30.0 30.9 32.4 35.5 12.0 22.0 30.6 31.8 32.4 31.1 31.5
[57] 11.3 19.4 25.8 27.9 28.5 28.1 27.8 10.5 14.9 18.1 18.9 19.5 22.2 21.9
[71]  7.7 11.4 12.3 13.0 12.5 13.7 14.4 10.6 18.0 17.9 17.9 17.9 18.9 19.9

Sometimes well want to focus on a specific range or subset of elements within a dataset. To do this, we use a colon. Think of the colon as representing the word through.

Using our CO2 dataset again, lets say we want to look at rows 5 through 7 and columns 2 through 4.

CO2[5:7,2:4]
    Type  Treatment conc
5 Quebec nonchilled  500
6 Quebec nonchilled  675
7 Quebec nonchilled 1000

Exercises

  1. When we started this lesson, we used R to calculate 2 + 5. How would we store the result of that calculation in an object?

  2. The c() function can create vectors from a list of numbers separated by commas, but it will also accept a colon. Use the c() function to create a vector of numbers 1 through 100 without having to type in each number. Store it as an object called bigVec.

  3. The sort() function allows us to sort elements in increasing or decreasing order. Use the help documentation in R to find out how to sort your bigVec object in decreasing order.

  4. R has a built-in dataset called iris. Use the head() function to get an idea of what it contains.

  5. The mean() function provides the average of a set of numbers. What is the average petal length of all the flowers in the iris dataset?
